Note:
EMAIL ADDRESS - RFC 5322 / RFC 5321 / RFC 6531 Email Primitive (Tier 1)

Implements the EmailAddress value type per RFC 5322 (Internet Message
Format), RFC 5321 (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol), and RFC 6531
(SMTP Extension for Internationalized Email Addresses).

Two validation modes are exposed:

  Strict mode: RFC 5322 / RFC 5321 ABNF strictly applied.
    - Local part 1..64 octets per RFC 5321 section 4.5.3.1.1
    - Domain part 1..255 octets per RFC 5321 section 4.5.3.1.2
    - Total length 3..256 octets
    - Local part characters limited to atom-text:
        ALPHA, DIGIT, and these specials: ! # $ % & ' * + - / = ? ^ _ ` { | } ~ .
      with the additional rule that '.' may not appear as the first or last
      character of the local part and may not occur consecutively.
    - Domain must satisfy the hostname grammar (RFC 1123) - this module
      does the bytewise structural check here; full domain validation is
      offered by net/domain.runa.
    - Quoted local-part forms are accepted: a leading '"' begins a quoted
      string in which most printable characters and escapes are permitted.

  Loose mode: same as strict but allows underscores anywhere in the domain
    and skips the dot-position rule on the local part. Useful for
    interpreting addresses found in legacy data sets.

Internationalized email (EAI) per RFC 6531:
  Allows UTF-8 bytes (>= 0x80) in the local part. The strict-mode validator
  rejects them; the EAI-aware validator accepts well-formed UTF-8 sequences
  per RFC 3629.

Record layout (24 bytes):
  offset 0:  local_part   (pointer to string)
  offset 8:  domain_part  (pointer to string)
  offset 16: is_quoted    (1 if local part was quoted in source, else 0)

Constants:
  EMAIL_MODE_STRICT, EMAIL_MODE_LOOSE, EMAIL_MODE_EAI
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/string_builder.runa" as SB
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/char_core.runa" as Char

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let EMAIL_LOCAL_MAX be 64
Let EMAIL_DOMAIN_MAX be 255
Let EMAIL_TOTAL_MAX be 256
Let EMAIL_RECORD_SIZE be 24
Let EMAIL_MODE_STRICT be 0
Let EMAIL_MODE_LOOSE be 1
Let EMAIL_MODE_EAI be 2

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CHARACTER PREDICATES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Check whether a single ASCII byte is a valid local-part atom character per
RFC 5322 section 3.2.3 atext production:
  ALPHA / DIGIT /
  "!" / "#" / "$" / "%" / "&" / "'" / "*" / "+" /
  "-" / "/" / "=" / "?" / "^" / "_" / "`" / "{" / "|" / "}" / "~"
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
ASCII alpha, ASCII digit, or one of the 21 specials enumerated above.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Used to enforce strict-mode validation; rejects path-traversal payloads
or shell-metachar local parts.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_is_atext" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ca be proc is_alpha from Char with ch
    If ca is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let cd be proc is_digit from Char with ch
    If cd is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 33:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 35:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 36:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 37:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 38:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 39:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 42:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 43:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 45:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 47:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 61:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 63:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 94:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 96:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 123:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 124:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 125:
        Return 1
    End If
    If ch is equal to 126:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOCAL PART VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Validate an unquoted local part per RFC 5322 dot-atom production:
  dot-atom-text = 1*atext *("." 1*atext)
RFC 5321 section 4.5.3.1.1 further limits length to 64 octets.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk byte-by-byte. Track whether the previous character was '.' to reject
consecutive dots. Reject leading or trailing dot. Reject any non-atext
byte in strict mode; accept UTF-8 lead bytes in EAI mode.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict mode is the safe default; loose mode is intended for parsers
ingesting historical data and should not be used for new validations.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_is_valid_local_part" takes local_str as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    If local_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than EMAIL_LOCAL_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let first be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with local_str, start
    If first is equal to 46:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let last be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with local_str, start plus length minus 1
    If last is equal to 46:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let prev_dot be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with local_str, start plus i
        If ch is equal to 46:
            If prev_dot is equal to 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            Set prev_dot to 1
        Otherwise:
            Set prev_dot to 0
            If ch is greater than 127:
                If mode is not equal to EMAIL_MODE_EAI:
                    Return 0
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Let ok be proc email_is_atext with ch
                If ok is equal to 0:
                    If mode is equal to EMAIL_MODE_LOOSE:
                        Note: In loose mode also accept '.', already handled above; other special bytes still rejected.
                        Return 0
                    Otherwise:
                        Return 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DOMAIN PART VALIDATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Validate the domain part using the RFC 1123 hostname grammar with the
RFC 5321 length cap of 255 octets. This is a bytewise check sufficient
for stage-1 acceptance; deeper IDN / DNS-resolvability checks belong to
net/domain.runa.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Split on '.'. Each label must be 1..63 octets and consist of letters,
digits, and hyphens with no leading or trailing hyphen.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Strict per RFC. Reject empty labels (consecutive dots) and labels with
non-LDH characters.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_is_valid_domain_part" takes domain_str as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    If domain_str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than EMAIL_DOMAIN_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let label_start be start
    Let label_len be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, start plus i
        If ch is equal to 46:
            If label_len is less than 1:
                Return 0
            End If
            If label_len is greater than 63:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let lstart be label_start
            Let first_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, lstart
            If first_b is equal to 45:
                Return 0
            End If
            Let last_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, lstart plus label_len minus 1
            If last_b is equal to 45:
                Return 0
            End If
            Set label_start to start plus i plus 1
            Set label_len to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let ca be proc is_alpha from Char with ch
            Let cd be proc is_digit from Char with ch
            If ca is equal to 0:
                If cd is equal to 0:
                    If ch is not equal to 45:
                        Return 0
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            Set label_len to label_len plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If label_len is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If label_len is greater than 63:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let first_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, label_start
    If first_b is equal to 45:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let last_b be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with domain_str, label_start plus label_len minus 1
    If last_b is equal to 45:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RECORD MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate and initialize a fresh EmailAddress record.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
24 bytes; all slots zeroed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_create" returns Integer:
    Let rec be proc allocate from Layout with EMAIL_RECORD_SIZE
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 0, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 8, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 16, 0
    Return rec
End Process

@Reasoning
Free an EmailAddress record and its owned component strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Free non-null component pointers then the record.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must not touch pointer after destroy.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_destroy" takes rec as Integer returns Integer:
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let local_p be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 0
    If local_p is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with local_p
    End If
    Let domain_p be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 8
    If domain_p is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with domain_p
    End If
    proc deallocate from Layout with rec
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "email_get_local_part" takes rec as Integer returns Integer:
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 0
End Process

Process called "email_get_domain" takes rec as Integer returns Integer:
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 8
End Process

Process called "email_is_quoted" takes rec as Integer returns Integer:
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 16
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARSE / FORMAT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Parse an email address per RFC 5322 / RFC 5321 / RFC 6531. The parser is
strict by default: the '@' separator must appear exactly once, neither
side may be empty, and component lengths must respect the RFC caps.

Mode parameter selects strict (default), loose (relaxed local-part dots),
or EAI (RFC 6531 internationalized).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Length check 3..256.
2. Locate the last '@' (per RFC 5321 the rightmost is the separator).
3. Validate local part via email_is_valid_local_part.
4. Validate domain part via email_is_valid_domain_part.
5. Allocate the record and store owned copies of both parts.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(n) for the two component copies.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Refuses partial or empty components, multiple '@' signs (counted), or
malformed length. Returns 0 on any failure so callers never receive a
partially-initialized record.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_parse" takes str as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let length be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    If length is less than 3:
        Return 0
    End If
    If length is greater than EMAIL_TOTAL_MAX:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: Locate rightmost '@'.
    Let at_pos be -1
    Let i be length minus 1
    Let scanning be 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        If scanning is equal to 1:
            Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Memory with str, i
            If ch is equal to 64:
                Set at_pos to i
                Set scanning to 0
            Otherwise:
                Set i to i minus 1
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set i to -1
        End If
    End While
    If at_pos is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    If at_pos is greater than or equal to length minus 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let local_len be at_pos
    Let domain_start be at_pos plus 1
    Let domain_len be length minus domain_start

    Let local_ok be proc email_is_valid_local_part with str, 0, local_len, mode
    If local_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let domain_ok be proc email_is_valid_domain_part with str, domain_start, domain_len
    If domain_ok is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let local_copy be proc string_substring from StringPrim with str, 0, local_len
    If local_copy is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let domain_copy be proc string_substring from StringPrim with str, domain_start, domain_len
    If domain_copy is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with local_copy
        Return 0
    End If

    Let rec be proc email_create
    If rec is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with local_copy
        proc deallocate from Layout with domain_copy
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 0, local_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 8, domain_copy
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with rec, 16, 0
    Return rec
End Process

@Reasoning
Render the email address back to its canonical "local@domain" string form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
StringBuilder concat with '@' between the two components.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(n). Space: O(n).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on null record or allocation failure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "email_to_string" takes rec as Integer returns Integer:
    If rec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let local_p be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 0
    Let domain_p be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with rec, 8
    If local_p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If domain_p is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sb be proc stringbuilder_create from SB
    If sb is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc stringbuilder_append from SB with sb, local_p
    proc stringbuilder_append_char from SB with sb, 64
    proc stringbuilder_append from SB with sb, domain_p
    Let result be proc stringbuilder_to_string from SB with sb
    proc stringbuilder_destroy from SB with sb
    Return result
End Process
